<TEXT>
they may prefer shuffleboard to 
sixpacks and naps to rap but senior citizens could become the 
life of the party in this former college spring break mecca 
a hotel operator organizing the first senior spring 
festival which begins friday hopes grayhaired sunseekers will 
flock each year to this seaside city that is attempting to shake 
off its bawdy image 
these arent what i would call party animals said philip 
goldfarb who put together the weekend activities were trying 
to attract an older crowd with events that we think theyll enjoy 
the estimated 5000 seniors will boogie on the beach to the 
tunes of the four tops and mingle on board a cruise ship but 
theres also an opportunity to pick up some tidbits at seminars on 
such sobering topics as finance and health 
the festivities are scheduled to conclude sunday with a brunch 
for grandparents and their grandchildren 
dont think of this as something trying to replace the college 
kids its obviously different said goldfarb were not 
talking about bikinis and beer were showing that theres options 
for the elderly to be active and social 
jogging along the beach in a spandex bodysuit 65yearold ellen 
witt smiled at the idea of her peers in a party mood 
why should the kids have all the fun youd be surprised what 
we can think up she said 
since a police crackdown drove off college spring breakers in 
the mid1980s city officials have been preoccupied with trying to 
recast fort lauderdale as a resort for families and international 
tourists 
but the transformation has been slowed by bureaucracic tangles 
and resistance from some business owners 
a proposal to redesign the seedy beach strip into upscale 
boutiques and hotels attracted only one bid from a developer whose 
multimilliondollar plan was rejected last week as unfeasible 
a ban on alcohol sale at nude dance clubs was passed by the city 
commission but business at the establishments remains brisk 
meanwhile the central florida theme parks and attractions 
continue to draw tourists from south florida beaches 
for 1989 the greater fort lauderdale convention amp visitors 
bureau estimated the area received 45 million tourists including 
a boost from the january 1989 super bowl but early figures for 
this year indicate a drop in tourist spending 
at the same time the number of college students visiting this 
spring fell below 20000 down from a record 350000 in 1985 
most of the students have adopted daytona beach as the new 
spring break capital but key west and the florida panhandle are 
also gaining popularity 
spring break is part of fort lauderdales past said 
goldfarb were looking at a different environment 
goldfarb says next years senior festival scheduled to 
coincide with a gerontology conference will be expanded to a week 
and promoted nationally he predicts up to 10000 oldsters could 
attend 
and some veterans of the college spring onslaught are wondering 
what to expect 
hey ill bring the surfboard and they can bring the beer 
said alan frank 24 sunning on a seawall with his girlfriend at 
least they dont have to worry about ids 
warren dipaulo 17 thought the concept was sweet 
why not he said party on dudes 
</TEXT>
