<TEXT>
ten years after his death communist 
yugoslavias founder josip broz tito faces a second demise the 
almost total negation of his oncevaunted accomplishments 
the tito myth which described him as a giant who achieved 
only great creations is now dead in yugoslavia the state news 
agency tanjug said in a commentary for the anniversary of titos 
death today 
formerly revered titos policies are now denounced official 
actions are under way throughout the nation to erase the traces of 
a personality cult that held sway for almost 40 years 
increasingly tito is under attack for his authoritarian style 
of rule the everfiercer feuds that have pitted serbs against 
nonserbs and liberals against orthodox communists are 
threatening to tear apart the very country tito built 
tito earned international recognition in 1948 for taking 
yugoslavia out of the soviet orbit and later making it a nonaligned 
nation 
since titos death at age 87 on may 4 1980 however yugoslavs 
increasingly have felt that most of their countrys current 
troubles took root during his 35 years of undisputed rule 
tito left yugoslavia with grave economic and ethnic problems and 
an impractical highly decentralized system of collective 
leadership with diluted responsibilities 
the lack of a strong central authority embodied by tito 
himself during his lifetime has now created two systems within 
one country threatening to pull yugoslavia apart 
the two most economically developed of yugoslavias six 
republics slovenia and croatia have held free elections their 
next step may be secession 
the largest republic serbia still advocates communism in the 
past two years however it has encouraged nationalism and 
veneration of its leader slobodan milosevic over reverence for 
tito 
the federal government has ordered traffic to stand still as 
sirens and horns wail friday at 305 pm the hour of titos death 
10 years ago 
but even such official respect is waning the federal parliament 
is expected soon to abolish a controversial law that makes public 
attacks on tito or his policies a crime punishable by up to three 
years in jail 
serbia formally opened parliamentary discussion of the highly 
unpopular law stating that titos policies should be evaluated on 
historical merit and not protected by the absurd law which 
only maintains his personality cult 
serbias communist officials and its media have led the attacks 
on tito a croat they claim his policies gave slovenia and croatia 
an economic edge at the expense of serbia 
newly founded parties in serbia also make attacks on tito a 
central part of their platform 
in an illustration of the deep antitito sentiments in serbia 
several tito portraits that the law says must hang in government 
and public offices have been covered up with calendars and photos 
of milosevic 
criticism of tito in other republics began by centering on his 
lavish lifestyle the former leader maintained more than 60 
residences and a fleet of luxurious cars and yachts 
increasingly however tito is under fire for punishing 
opponents former inmates of one of modern europes most brutal 
prison camps on goli otok bare island off the central adriatic 
coast now appear on television openly accusing tito of creating 
the camp 
new publications say up to 5000 prosoviet communists who 
opposed titos break with moscow died in the camp between 1948 and 
the mid1950s 
even in his native croatia tito is attacked by men he purged as 
alleged croatian nationalists in 1971 several have now returned to 
politics doing well in free elections 
official initiatives are under way in slovenia and montenegro to 
return the original names to cities and streets named after tito 
following world war ii 
plans to erect monuments to tito in yugoslavias main cities 
have been scrapped allegedly for economic reasons 
the prominent croatian monthly start ironically proposed an 
alternative project a titoland amusement park in titos 
native croatian town of kumrovec 
in another dig at tito recent articles and books reveal alleged 
details of the leaders private life with his wife jovanka 
mrs broz who is fighting a court battle with the state over 
what she claims are her and her late husbands personal belongings 
is kept under virtual house arrest in belgrade unable to give 
interviews or appear in public 
in a letter printed in the belgrade politika daily mrs broz 
protested publications about her life with tito saying they are 
all a part of a long campaign against my husband and myself 
</TEXT>
