<TEXT>
the bush administration has been making 
friendly noises lately toward some countries more accustomed to 
scorn than sweet talk 
old rivals iran and syria are being praised for their role in 
helping win the release of american hostages there even is 
evidence of a thaw with two marxist countries that washington has 
long ignored albania and south yemen 
this week the administration is entertaining the deputy prime 
minister of mongolia daskiin byambasuren the highest ranking 
official from that country to visit washington since it entered the 
soviet orbit in 1921 
three years ago the united states and mongolia were not on 
speaking terms now they are talking about a trade agreement 
but theres one old foe where the us attitude has been far 
less accommodating vietnam it was 15 years ago this week that the 
communist conquest of vietnam was completed with the collapse of 
the saigon government and the humiliating us departure from that 
country 
vietnam seems ready for the woundhealing process but the 
united states has put up a host of imposing barriers 
washington is demanding that vietnam find a solution to the 
decadelong conflict in cambodia and that hanoi withdraw all its 
forces from that country permanently the united states also wants 
a maximum accounting for more than 2300 us troops still listed 
as missing in action in vietnam 
by making normalization subject to onerous conditions the 
administration is leaving the impression that it is psychologically 
difficult for it to make gestures toward the country responsible 
for americas greatest military defeat 
time magazine chided the administration this week for its tough 
stance asserting that washington continues to act as if hanoi 
had sent its troops to invade virginia instead of down the ho chi 
minh trail 
if the administration really were interested in a normal 
relationship it could rationalize it easily a spokesman could 
explain it this way 
we are prepared to look to the future instead of the past in 
our relations with vietnam it is logical for the united states to 
want diplomatic access to the third largest communist country in 
the world we believe a diplomatic presence in hanoi would enhance 
the possibility of achieving our objectives in that region 
a timecnn poll indicates the administration may be out of step 
with public opinion on the vietnam question three out of five 
respondents favor an exchange of ambassadors with hanoi 
but the wall street journal believes administration policy is 
right on the mark 
vietnam remains a bastion of repression and a threat to its 
neighbors the journal editorialized it is important to insist 
that it first become a civilized nation before offering it friendly 
gestures in asia there has been no crackup of communist 
dictatorships neither has there been any significant reduction in 
the pacific military might of vietnams big brother the soviet 
union 
but the state of us relations with vietnam is not all 
negative hanoi has been far more accommodating lately in providing 
an accounting of missing servicemen and in allowing former 
detainees held on political charges to emigrate to the united 
states the offspring of american servicemen also are being given 
permission to emigrate in larger numbers 
and there has been a significant expansion in us private 
humanitarian assistance to vietnam since 1987 the us government 
has been actively encouraging private groups to send aid to 
vietnamese war victims and to children 
us officials said that as a result there has easily been a 
fourfold increase in the number of us groups involved in these 
tasks and in the value of the assistance provided 
vietnams foreign minister nguyen co thach wishes the goodwill 
shown by private americans would extend to us officials 
when i meet people from the state department their faces 
never smile he said it is a pity 
</TEXT>
