<TEXT>
the united states is giving up deploying new 
landbased nuclear missiles in europe but many other 
lesspublicized nuclear arms already are in the pipeline 
private analysts said thursday the littleknown new weapons 
such as a shortrange missile fired from submarines would more 
than offset the loss of firepower from president bushs decision 
not to modernize the landbased lance missile 
its like trading two handguns for an assault rifle said 
daniel plesch director of the british american security 
information council a private arms group 
bush on thursday also announced cancellation of a modernized 
155mm nucleartipped artillery shell although he did not say that 
existing shells in europe would be withdrawn 
the decisions had been widely anticipated even though bush 
strenuously argued in favor of these weapons last year west 
germany and other nato allies oppose the weapons 
bush made no mention of the other nuclear weapons already 
planned for european deployment private experts said nato will be 
getting more than its giving up 
already in the american nuclear arsenal in europe are an 
estimated 1400 freefall bombs carried by the f111 and other 
europeanbased aircraft about 1200 artillery shells 200 depth 
bombs to kill submarines and 700 aging lance missiles 
the most important new weapon earmarked for european deployment 
is an airtosurface nuclear missile that could be carried on the 
american f16 fighters based in europe and the new f15e nuclear 
strike aircraft now in production 
the leading candidate for an airtosurface missile is the 
shortrange attack missiletactical which the air force is 
reported to be developing with a range of about 250 miles 
william arkin an arms expert with the environmental group 
greenpeace usa said the air force wants to start deploying the 
airtosurface missile in europe by 1995 with a total purchase for 
european use of about 300 missiles 
the advantage of an airtosurface missile is that it would give 
the air forces of the north atlantic treaty organization a 
capability in the event of a nuclear war to stand off from 
the battlefront and still hit soviet territory 
the united states now has no airtosurface nuclear missiles in 
europe britain and france reportedly are cooperating to develop 
their own missiles of this type 
the nowcanceled lance missile which was to replace the 
existing lance arsenal would not have been capable of reaching 
soviet territory 
bush did not say he would withdraw any of the existing lances 
and plesch said it was possible that nato could agree to refurbish 
them to extend their useful lives the pentagon has said the lances 
are due to become obsolete by the mid1990s 
among other weapons in the pipeline are more us shorterrange 
nuclear missiles for deployment on attack submarines based in the 
north atlantic and the mediterranean arkin said about 350 of 
these called the tomahawk land attack missile already have been 
deployed bushs 1991 budget calls for buying 75 more 
the pentagon also is developing new versions of its nuclear 
gravity bombs and antisubmarine depth bombs 
the soviet union also has a large shortrange nuclear 
capability although it is unclear how their deployments may be 
affected by the demise of the warsaw pact as a cohesive military 
force 
the soviets have urged immediate negotiations to eliminate all 
shorterrange nuclear weapons in europe but the bush 
administration has refused nato leaders decided last year they 
would put off any such negotiations until after an eastwest treaty 
is signed to reduce nonnuclear weapons in europe 
arkin said the soviets have more than 1400 launchers for 
shortrange nuclear systems based on land including about 660 frog 
missiles built in the 1960s 300 ss21 missiles that are equivalent 
to the us lance missiles and about 500 scudb missiles 
</TEXT>
