properly insured safeguarded and displayed 
i think its that kind of an item that can do nothing but good 
if it was on public display hoffman said since i first saw it 
i think i have become a more spiritual person 
hoffman and barbish bought the pearl for 200000 from the 
estate of american archaeologist wilburn d cobb in 1980 cobb 
received it from a moslem tribal chief in the philippines whose son 
cobb had treated for malaria 
barbish became entangled in a legal dispute with two other 
people he sold an interest to and a court ordered the pearl sold 
as part of the settlement 
according to the legend the pearl grew to its present size as 
it was handed down for centuries to laotzus descendants the 
descendants would periodically replant the gem in bigger clams 
allowing it to continue to grow 
the pearl and the giant clam that was holding it were lost in a 
typhoon that hit the philippines sometime during the ming dynasty 
which ruled china from 1368 to 1644 
it was recovered in 1934 by a filipino diver who reportedly 
drowned trying to take it away from the clam 
eventually brought to the surface it became the property of a 
moslem tribal chief who said it resembled the turbanwrapped head 
of mohammed thus it acquired the name pearl of allah 
