<TEXT>
a promised 24billionayear shift of federal 
tax burden to corporations is not materializing and individuals are 
making up the difference the government says 
but the news is not as bad as it might sound for individual 
taxpayers their share of the federal burden is dropping and they 
are paying about 24 billion a year more than forecast only because 
their incomes are rising faster than predicted 
witnesses told the senate finance committee on thursday that the 
inability to make precise estimates is chiefly to blame for the 
fact that corporations are paying less taxes than were anticipated 
when congress wrote the landmark 1986 tax overhaul 
approximately 58 percent of the shortfall in corporate income 
tax receipts over the 198789 period is attributable to 
lowerthanexpected projected profits robert d reischauer 
director of the congressional budget office told the committee 
corporate profits are volatile and therefore notoriously 
difficult to forecast reischauer said 
the primary reason is that pretax corporate profits came 
in below expectations harvey s rosen deputy assistant 
secretary of the treasury agreed 
one reason that corporate earnings were lower than expected is 
that individual incomes rose faster than projected witnesses 
testified those wage increases gave individuals larger taxable 
incomes and because wages are a deductible expense gave 
corporations less taxable income 
robert mcintyre director of the laborfunded citizens for tax 
justice blamed the tax shortfall on a tendency for corporations to 
borrow rather than issue stock to finance expansion this 
borrowing wave was highlighted in the late 1980s by corporate 
takeovers financed by leveraged buyouts 
corporations are sending their profits to bondholders rather 
than paying dividends to shareholders and taxes to the treasury 
mcintyre said 
rosen the treasury official said available evidence suggests 
little connection between buyout borrowing and the tax shortage 
a major goal of the 1986 tax overhaul was to shift about 24 
billion a year of tax burden from individuals to corporations in 
the 198789 period corporate taxes fell 63 billion short of 
congressional budget office forecasts and 65 billion below the 
administration estimate 
when the new law was approved the government estimated that 
individual income taxes would average 391 billion a year in 
198789 collections actually averaged 413 billion a year 
the corporate share of income taxes rose from 15 percent in 1986 
to 19 percent in 1989 rosen said while the individual share 
dropped from 85 percent to 81 percent 
even so reischauer said corporate taxes have failed to keep 
pace with economic growth corporate taxes measured 4 percent of 
gross national product in 1960 by 1986 the amount had declined to 
15 percent he said 
