the bush administration is playing down the 
lack of progress in strengthening the shaky japanese yen as 
economic chiefs from the worlds major industrial powers prepare 
for a weekend gathering 
only a month ago the socalled group of seven promised to work 
against the weak yens undesirable consequences for the world 
economy and us trade deficit nevertheless the yens value 
remains near a threeyear low against the dollar 
a weak yen tends to hurt the trade deficit by making american 
goods more expensive in japan and japanese goods more affordable in 
the united states 
a senior treasury department official briefing reporters 
thursday on condition of anonymity sought to minimize rate 
problems by noting the stability of currency markets since the 
group of sevens april 7 meeting in paris 
coordinated yen buying by major central banks around the world 
has helped prevent the japanese currency from falling further 
however the official conceded that us officials continue to 
be concerned about the general level of the yen which by april 
had fallen more than 10 percent against the dollar since the start 
of the year 
the official said exchange rates will be among the topics 
covered sunday when finance ministers and central bank chiefs from 
the united states japan west germany great britain france 
canada and italy confer in advance of the spring meetings of the 
152nation international monetary fund and the world bank 
finance officials also will be wrestling with the politically 
touchy problem of increasing the resources of the imf reviewing 
progress in easing the crushing 13 trillion debt burden on third 
world countries and evaluating west germanys plans to forge a 
monetary union with east germany 
some private economists accuse the group of seven of minimizing 
exchange rate problems because they cannot agree on how to fix them 
c fred bergsten a former treasury official who now heads the 
washington think tank the institute for international economics 
warned that the us trade gap which has fallen for the past two 
years could soon start growing again 
i think theres a strange sense of complacency among the g7 
members except for the japanese when officials cant come up with 
solutions they tend to deny problems so they dont look 
ineffective in solving them bergsten said 
