<TEXT>
senate democrats and republicans are laying 
out sharply contrasting proposals to change the way their campaigns 
are financed with each party seeking to protect the current 
advantages it enjoys 
democrats on thursday unveiled a package to slash in half the 
amount of money candidates now raise and spend on campaigns by 
imposing ceilings with a lure that the government would pick up 
part of the remaining tab 
republicans claiming it is the source of money rather than the 
amount spent that is corrupting politics had announced a proposal 
tuesday to outlaw political action committees and effectively 
prohibit unions from underwriting campaigns 
both parties embrace proposals to encourage candidates to rely 
more on small contributions of less than 100 250 or 1000 from 
instate donors 
however critics said the plans leave large loopholes for 
raising socalled special interest money through national and state 
party organizations 
the democratic plan for example would outlaw pac contributions 
to individual candidates but still allow the two national parties 
to raise up to 5 million from such sources and their house and 
senate campaign committees even more 
and state party organizations under both plans could still raise 
large amounts via directmail drives and from wealthy individuals 
in case of the gop and for democrats through those sources plus 
unions and pacs 
does it need to be improved of course it does said joan 
claybrook president of public citizen a group that advocates 
total federal financing of campaigns but to me its a giant 
step 
under the democratic plan about 70 percent of a federal 
candidates general election campaign expenses but none of the 
costs for primary races would be paid by the government from 
money raised through a proposed 3 checkoff on income tax returns 
through the checkoff taxpayers could voluntarily designate 3 
of the refunds they are due or add 3 to the taxes they owe for a 
special government account to finance congressional races 
since the middle 1970s tax returns have included a checkoff 
that allows taxpayers to designate 1 of their owed taxes to a fund 
for financing presidential campaigns 
the new ceilings that democrats are proposing on senate 
campaigns are about 20 percent higher than in a previous democratic 
package reported out of the senate rules committee two months ago 
covering both primary and general elections the new limits 
would range from 19 million in small states to slightly more than 
10 million in the most populous california 
were not going to get hung up on the percentages or the 
specific amounts said sen david boren dokla the chief 
author of the package everything is negotiable from our point of 
view except that we have to have some limit on overall spending 
republicans reacted with disdain to the proposal sen mitch 
mcconnell of kentucky the partys point man on the issue said the 
combination of public financing and campaign ceilings would sharply 
curtail the gops ability to regain control of congress 
including house races taxpayers would pick up a 400 million 
tab each election cycle for an incumbents protection bill 
mcconnell said unless youre a sitting governor or a movie star 
no challenger is ever again going to win a political race 
sen joseph biden ddel said democrats embraced a bigger role 
for public financing after rejecting it earlier out of a sense of 
vulnerability in the wake of recent campaign financing scandals 
the biggest of those is the keating five senators under 
investigation by an ethics panel for interceding with savings and 
loan regulators on behalf of phoenix financier charles h keating 
jr after accepting 13 million in campaign gifts from him 
what were all willing to trade off is the vulnerability of 
having a wellfunded legitimate opponent because with public 
financing thats a guarantee versus the vulnerability of having 
our reputations ruined and not being able to defend ourselves 
biden said 
