<TEXT>
a former city prosecutor won a record 34 
million libel suit against the philadelphia inquirer in a case that 
stemmed from newspaper stories written 17 years ago 
a common pleas court jury on thursday awarded 25 million in 
compensatory damages and 315 million in punitive damages to 
lawyer richard a sprague a former first assistant district 
attorney 
the decision was the largest award ever against the news media 
surpassing the 28 million won last month by a heart surgeon 
against a san antonio television station 
the judgment was more than seven times the 45 million verdict 
that the inquirer had successfully appealed from the first trial in 
the case 
sprague sued in 1983 over articles dating to 1973 that 
questioned his actions and decisions as a prosecutor 
his attorney james e beasley said the jurys verdict sent a 
message to investigative reporters not to destroy somebodys 
reputation 
inquirer executive editor and president eugene l roberts jr 
said the newspaper would appeal the decision 
the award amounts to about onethird of the newspapers net 
worth said the inquirers attorney samuel e klein roberts said 
the newspaper would be able to stay in business if the judgment 
stands but we would be crippled 
the inquirer has won 17 pulitzer prizes in the last 16 years 
many of them stemming from investigative stories 
a libel case observer said thursday the huge award stood little 
chance of surviving an appeals challenge 
based on the trends one would have to assume that this award 
cannot stand up on appeal said henry kaufman general counsel of 
the libel defense resource center in new york 
kaufman said only two libel judgments of more than 1 million 
have been affirmed on appeal 
i am a very strong advocate of first amendment rights said 
beasley what i dont tolerate and i dont think society should 
tolerate is the use of investigative reporters or the power of the 
press for a personal vendetta and that is what developed here 
he said greg walter one of the reporters involved in the 
stories had threatened to get and destroy sprague who had 
prosecuted walter in 1972 for taping a conversation without the 
other persons knowledge 
walter has since died 
