<TEXT>
penicillinresistant gonorrhea more than doubled 
from 1988 to 1989 and its treatment will require more expensive 
drugs federal researchers say 
a survey of 21 clinics that treat sexually transmitted disease 
found penicillinresistant gonorrhea increased 131 percent in the 
oneyear period the national centers for disease control said 
thursday 
tetracyclineresistant gonorrhea increased by 23 percent in the 
same period the survey found 
during the study period the national gonorrhea rate of 
infection remained basically unchanged with three cases reported 
in every 1000 americans 
the traditional and admittedly inexpensive therapies for 
gonorrhea penicillin and tetracycline really in many situations 
are not going to be the appropriate drugs for treating gonorrhea in 
1990 said william whittington a cdc specialist in sexually 
transmitted diseases 
the cdc survey found gonorrhea strains susceptible to two 
typically more expensive drugs ceftriaxone and spectinomycin 
ceftriaxone or similar treatment remains an integral component 
of the strategy for gonorrhea control the cdc said 
in the survey 20 male gonorrhea patients were tested each month 
for drug resistance 
resistance to penicillin which occurred in 32 percent of the 
study cases in 1988 increased to 74 percent in 1989 the cdc said 
resistance to tetracycline which occurred in 4 percent of the 
study cases in 1988 increased to 49 percent in 1989 the cdc said 
significant increases in penicillin resistance were reported 
at seven clinics atlanta birmingham ala boston long beach 
calif philadelphia san antonio and san diego 
penicillinresistant cases made up 32 percent of the cases in the 
long beach clinic last year 
significant increases in tetracycline resistance were reported 
in birmingham denver st louis and west palm beach fla while 
decreases were observed in atlanta and baltimore the highest rate 
of tetracycline resistance last year 20 percent was in 
philadelphia 
nationwide 738160 cases of gonorrhea were reported last year 
so far this year 215011 cases have been reported down slightly 
from 216088 at the same point in 1989 
