<DOCNO> AP900504-0058 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
five driftnet fishing boats spotted in 
unauthorized areas are marked with north korean flags which would 
signal a new player in an international fray over use of such nets 
and high seas salmon fishing authorities said 
north korea has no diplomatic ties or fisheries treaties with 
the united states 
were trying to establish whether they are in fact north 
korean and if they are north korean why they have suddenly 
appeared out there this year said coast guard capt david a 
wirth in juneau 
we have never seen them before he said we dont know why 
theyre there 
the coast guard is tracking the ships with aircraft wirth said 
the ships were spotted tuesday by a coast guard plane officials 
said thursday they were fishing about 400 miles southwest of kiska 
island near the end of the aleutian chain in waters where 
driftnets likely would intercept salmon from north america 
while most driftnets ostensibly are set for squid critics say 
they illegally snag millions of dollars worth of us and canadian 
salmon the critics liken the floating nets stretching as long as 
30 miles to stripmining of the sea 
the ships flew north korean flags and had north korean markings 
on their smokestacks and bows coast guard officials said thursday 
four similar ships were spotted in the same area april 22 and 
24 the coast guard said 
its possible the north korean insignia is a disguise by vessels 
from other nations that could be pirating salmon in violation of 
agreements with the united states wirth said or the ships may be 
north korean on contract with other nations he said 
the united states has negotiated treaties with south korea 
japan and taiwan prohibiting the taking of north american salmon by 
driftnets it has a tentative agreement with the soviet union to 
cooperate to stop illegal salmon fishing in the north pacific us 
officials have asked the soviet union for help in investigating the 
ships 
our government called in the soviet fisheries attache 
wednesday and requested assistance said bill woolf fisheries 
aide to us sen frank h murkowski ralaska 
we hope the soviets will do their best to dissuade the north 
koreans if indeed these ships are theirs from high seas salmon 
fishing at best and at the very least to assist us in gathering 
information on the extent and duration of this fishery and if they 
have information on where the product is going woolf said 
coast guard photographs show the five ships appear to be new 
and are very well kept up with gobs and gobs of sophisticated 
electronics woolf said 
theyre not typical of the usual japanese and taiwanese 
driftnet fishing vessels which see some pretty rough usage he 
said 
photographs also show fish on the ships decks 
the ships may be violating the 1976 magnuson act which in part 
protects fish spawned in us rivers said henry mitchell 
