the postal service is planning to sell 
polyester postage stamps through automatic teller machines at banks 
in a sixmonth test beginning may 18 in seattle 
spokesman art shealy announced thursday that the stamps will be 
testmarketed in a joint venture by the postal service and seafirst 
bank first at about 15 seattle locations and then at other 
seafirst branches in washington state 
shealy said the sheets of stamps were designed to resemble 
currency so that they can be dispensed the same way cash is 
dispensed through the machines 
he said the sheets each with a dozen 25cent stamps would cost 
3 apiece debited against the customers bank account 
the stamp is designed to be selfadhesive requiring no licking 
shealy said 
we think it answers quite a large portion of the publics 
request for a more convenient stamp he said it is 
humidityresistant so they dont stick together it is really a 
stamp of the future 
if the seattle test is a success shealy said the stamps will 
be tried out nationwide in the spring of 1991 
