ministers of britain france and the two german nations to discuss 
one of the trickiest obstacles to creating a united germany 
figuring out how to keep it from disrupting the european balance of 
power 
there are widespread concerns in europe that a stronger germany 
could again pose a threat to countries overrun during the two world 
wars 
the soviet union has consistently ruled out nato membership for 
a united germany 
we consider a unified germany as an important factor of 
stability and peace in europe shevardnadze said today for 
such a giant to belong to one bloc one alliance will not 
create conditions for stability 
the soviets have called for a neutral germany 
the united states and its nato partners view membership in the 
alliance as the best insurance policy at their meeting thursday 
they agreed germany would not have nuclear or chemical weapons and 
insisted that a united germany belongs in nato 
in a move that appeared aimed at allaying soviet security 
concerns the foreign ministers supported allowing soviet troops to 
remain in east germany after unification during a transition period 
until now east germany has served both as a loyal soviet 
military ally and a buffer against us nuclear missiles and troops 
in west germany 
