britains labor party rejoiced friday in sweeping 
local election victories but prime minister margaret thatcher took 
comfort that the results were not as devastating to her 
conservatives as expected 
and some analysts predicted mrs thatcher was now more secure 
against possible challenges to her leadership of the conservative 
party 
millions of voters protesting soaring home loan rates and an 
unpopular new local tax deserted the conservatives in the 
nationwide local vote thursday 
but while preelection polls showed mrs thatcher with a 
20point deficit the actual swing against the government was only 
11 percent share prices rose on the london stock exchange 
reflecting relief by big business 
in the most important trend for labor the party posted 
significant gains in the prosperous and heavily populated south for 
the first time since mrs thatcher ousted a labor government in 
1979 
that is the spread of support that we need which makes me 
forecast that we are certain to win the next election said labor 
party leader neil kinnock 
