more than 200 human skulls have been found 
in caves near a guerrilla camp high in the andean mountains but 
authorities said they did not know who the dead were 
a medical examiner who accompanied an army patrol to the caves 
said some of the victims had died violently and in the past two 
years but that other remains might be hundreds of years old 
army sources said some of the bones may be those of rebels 
fatally wounded in clashes with the military and the police others 
may be those of guerrillas who tried to desert or of peasants 
kidnapped from nearby villages 
the caves are located 14200 feet above sea level 20 miles 
north of this andean city ayacucho is the birthplace of the 
maoistinspired shining path guerrilla movement and rebels control 
much of the surrounding countryside 
the skulls and other human bones were found last month by a 
civil defense group on the lookout for shining path rebels near 
the caves the group found 200 sticks of dynamite medicines 
knives and rebel propaganda 
a military patrol from ayacucho 235 miles southeast of lima 
went to investigate the groups findings the patrol accompanied 
by an associated press reporter returned to ayacucho friday 
the medical examiner speaking on condition of anonymity said 
many of the bones in the two caves were quite old and could have 
been placed there hundreds of years ago 
he said he was unable to count the exact number of skulls of 
recent origin 
but some of the recently dead apparently were killed by bullet 
or machete wounds the examiner said 
more than 18000 people have died in political violence since 
the shining path began its armed insurgency 10 years ago 
