westrate one of the deas chief spokesmen on capitol hill was 
burkes boss until burke was named deputy administrator of the dea 
last year burke has become acting administrator since the 
retirement of former administrator john c lawn 
the bush administration has not yet nominated a permanent 
replacement for lawn but both westrate and burke are among those 
being considered for the job according to justice department 
sources who spoke on condition of anonymity 
westrate has held the job directing deas worldwide operations 
since august 1985 and has generally spoken for the dea at 
congressional hearings 
replacing westrate as operations director would be stephen h 
greene who has been westrates deputy for about a year said 
shults greene was also burkes replacement when burke became 
deputy administrator to lawn 
peter f gruden who has been assistant administrator for 
planning and inspection for several years would become the special 
agent in charge of the washington field office shults said 
the chief of the washington field office ronald j caffrey 
would replace greene as the deputy assistant administrator for 
operations under burkes reorgnization 
our agents normally rotate to different jobs every two to 
three years shults said executives dont rotate that often 
because there arent that many jobs available for them 
shults said these latest moves dont mean anything in terms 
of change in dea policy and are not meant to be critical of 
anyones performance 
westrate did not immediately respond to a request for comment 
