<TEXT>
a 34 million libel judgment against the 
philadelphia inquirer raises serious constitutional questions and 
will likely be overturned on appeal a media lawyer and a 
reporters group said friday 
a common pleas court jury on thursday awarded 25 million in 
compensatory damages and 315 million in punitive damages to 
former first assistant district attorney richard sprague he sued 
the paper over stories published 17 years ago that questioned his 
actions as a prosecutor 
its unimaginable to me that a punitive damage award in this 
amount could or would be upheld said floyd abrams a prominent 
first amendment lawyer he represents nbc in appealing a 53 
million libel judgment won by entertainer wayne newton 
this is another example of libel law running amok abrams 
said i think that this case and others will sooner rather than 
later lead the supreme court to address the constitutionality of 
punitive damages in libel cases 
henry kaufman general counsel of the libel defense resource 
center a mediasponsored clearinghouse in new york said the 
judgment was the largest ever against the news media he said only 
two libel judgments of more than 1 million have been affirmed on 
appeal 
sprague now a successful attorney in private practice won for 
the second time before a jury in the case the inquirer had earlier 
successfully appealed a 45 million verdict less than 
oneseventh the amount of thursdays award which sprague said gave 
meaning to the idea of punitive damages 
i intend to fight to maintain it sprague said friday the 
whole theory of punitive damages is that it should not just be a 
little slap on the wrist its got to be meaningful 
a tendency for juries to grant everhigher punitive damages has 
come under scrutiny in other areas recently 
last month the supreme court agreed to decide in an alabama 
insurance fraud case whether punitive damage awards can be so great 
as to become unconstitutional 
the court last year ruled large awards in civil suits do not 
violate the constitutions ban on excessive fines but the court 
did not address the question of whether such awards violate due 
process protections 
punitive damages in general are dangerous abrams said in 
libel cases they are perilous juries are given no standards no 
limits no bounds and sometimes they act that way 
in the philadelphia case jurors were given only the newspapers 
net worth 102 million in determining how to set the punitive 
damages the newspaper was not allowed to cite spragues income 
which forbes magazine estimated at 16 million in 1988 
common pleas court judge charles p mirarchi jr said the jury 
had to find outrageous conduct and that it could set an award to 
punish the inquirer and to send a message to the rest of the news 
media 
my basic opinion is that the law is fair and the jury must 
make that determination not the judge mirarchi said 
jane kirtley executive director of the reporters committee for 
freedom of the press sees a first amendment issue in such awards 
all a punitive damage award is when its awarded against a 
news organization is a fine for speaking she said but beyond 
that it doesnt have to bear any relationship to anything 
reed irvine chairman of accuracy in media a conservative 
