inquirer 
the amounts involved here are almost ruinous in a sense 
irvine said i think thats going too far myself its legitimate 
to give em a good hard rap across the knuckles but its another 
to take it out of their hide 
the groups director of media analysis former philadelphia 
inquirer staffer joseph goulden said such awards are saying what 
the publics saying about the press the only way to enforce a code 
of ethics is in the courtroom 
abrams said he was worried about the impact on news gathering 
punitive damages have the potential for so chilling speech that 
the public would lose a significant amount of the most important 
news that reporters present 
