afghan soldiers battled islamic 
guerrillas around the eastern city of jalalabad on friday hours 
after the government ended its 15month state of emergency in the 
country staterun radio reported 
kabul radio monitored in islamabad said a number of 
political opponents were killed in the fighting and large amounts 
of weapons and ammunition destroyed it said nothing of government 
casualties 
the radio said forces loyal to president najibullah recaptured 
key outposts around the city in an offensive that began tuesday 
fighting has flared and faded since the guerrillas attempted a 
conventional assault on jalalabad in march 1989 three weeks after 
the soviet union withdrew its troops from afghanistan 
the radio also said government forces pushed back guerrillas 
surrounding the southern cities of kandahar and khost with heavy 
fighting and aerial bombardment under way 
the guerrillas known as mujahedeen or islamic holy warriors 
said up to 165 soldiers at khost were killed or wounded when 
government planes bombed the garrison wednesday in the fear the 
soldiers planned to defect 
the reports could not be independently verified 
emergency rule was lifted at midnight thursday najibullah who 
uses only one name had promised it would end by may 20 
the emergency was imposed just after soviet troops ended nine 
years of direct involvement and pulled out of afghanistan in 
february 1989 the decree gave najibullah power to override 
parliament and placed afghanistans defense under the control of a 
supreme military council 
lifting the emergency cleared the way for constitutional reforms 
aimed at ending the 12yearold war which has killed more than 1 
million people destroyed much of the country and ruined its 
economy 
