<TEXT>
ethanol used in nuclear waste storage tanks 
at the hanford nuclear reservation could ignite the us 
department of energy said friday it was the third report of an 
explosive hazard there in nine months 
but federal officials state regulators and hanford critics all 
played down the ethanol problem friday saying it was easy to fix 
the air of calm was in contrast to earlier revelations about 
explosive threats from ferrocyanide and a hydrogen gas buildup 
this will be resolved in the next few days said ken morgan 
of the does richland operations office in a telephone interview 
jim thomas of the spokanebased hanford education action league 
said the ethanol danger is not as serious as the potential danger 
from the hydrogen gas buildup but was another example of inept 
management by the energy department 
they were introducing a potentially energetic chemical in 
tanks that have very dangerous wastes in them thomas said 
this has gone on for years 
the latest concern centers on the tubes that run the length of 
hanfords giant nuclear waste storage tanks 
the tubes contain probes that use sound waves to take readings 
of the contents of the tanks the tubes are filled with liquid to 
better conduct the sound morgan said usually the liquid is water 
but during cold months an antifreeze ethanol is added he said 
there were six tubes recently tested and in one case the ethanol 
fumes were gathering at the top of the tube in a potentially 
explosive quantity morgan said 
the suspect tube will either be diluted with water or pumped 
out morgan said 
the tubes are about three inches in diameter and 45 feet long 
and sealed at the bottom so nothing inside them actually makes 
contact with the waste morgan said 
ethanol has been used for years in the monitoring tubes of many 
tanks said mike berriochoa of westinghouse hanford co the 
government contractor that operates the hanford tank farms 
berriochoa said he was not sure how many tubes westinghouse would 
need to remove ethanol from 
the exploding tanks controversy began last october when the 
staff of sen john glenn dohio released a 1984 report that 
concluded some storage tanks at hanford contained ferrocyanide that 
could explode 
a flurry of analyses has since concluded that the risk from 
ferrocyanide is quite low 
but in studying that issue doe scientists uncovered a new 
threat from hydrogen gas that was building up underneath the hard 
crust inside about 20 waste storage tanks at hanford 
the energy department announced that hazard in late march and 
said they could not guarantee an explosion would not occur that 
produced a whole new round of tank studies which so far have 
concluded that the explosion risk is low but the energy department 
also admits it does not yet have enough data for a solution 
morgan acknowledged that extensive criticism focusing on the 
energy department in the recent controversies prompted officials to 
call reporters with the latest news 
were a little touchy he said 
hanford has 177 nuclear waste storage tanks which contain the 
highly radioactive byproducts of more than 40 years of plutonium 
production for nuclear weapons 
