<TEXT>
caryl churchill doesnt make things easy for an 
audience 
the proof is currently on stage at the new york shakespeare 
festival public theater where a double bill of two short works by 
the english playwright is puzzling theatergoers 
the title ice cream with hot fudge is deceptively sweet 
the two plays are not 
hot fudge the shorter and more arcane of the plays begins 
with a chorus of lowerclass brits plotting an intricate 
checkcashing scam their greed is similiar to the moneygrubbing 
celebrated by the stockbrokers churchill skewered in serious 
money her last new york outing 
much of the dialogue in hot fudge is overlapping making it 
impossible to understand clearly you get the idea if not the 
actual words the avarice goes upscale in the next scene or two 
when ruby margaret whitton pairs off with colin john pankow and 
meets his wealthy friends 
people talk about their careers in global industry or their 
selfdevelopment vacations or their homes as investments 
but theres a nastiness underneath the chic cocktail chatter that 
doesnt become apparent until ruby is confronted by colins exwife 
julianne moore the confrontation and the play end in 
violence and the bleak realization that nothing is as it seems 
ice cream composed of 20 short scenes is the more 
substantial dangerous dessert the black often bewildering 
comedy illustrates churchills disenchantment with romantic notions 
of both england and the united states 
two innocent american tourists lance and vera find delight in 
everything british from the way the natives say ice cream to 
all those ancient buildings to even discovering distant cousins of 
lances 
but these relatives are not mr micawber and mary poppins they 
are vindictive uncouth slightly menacing people who end up 
murdering their landlord and they draw their american cousins into 
the crime 
when the english brother and sister visit america they are 
similiarly misinformed about the habits of the foreign land but 
churchills scalpel is not nearly as sharp in her dissection of 
american life and culture her portrait of two rural bumpkins for 
example seems straight out of the beverely hillbillies only 
not as funny 
the violence the british couple committed in england follows 
them to america and it dogs the american husband and wife too 
its a chilly link between the two nations 
the play ends weirdly unexpectedly in fact many in the 
audience at a recent performance didnt know it was over until the 
actors came out to take their bows 
the cast is competent rather than inspired except for john 
pankow who plays the disturbed colin in hot fudge and a 
variety of very different small roles in ice cream with 
distinction 
director les waters certainly keeps the plays moving quickly 
helped by the minimal settings of stark sliding walls churchills 
plays are just as stark keeping the audience offbalance but that 
may be her main goal 
ice cream with hot fudge is more unnerving than entertaining 
