<TEXT>
a fading cold war and growing 
philippine nationalism may cause the united states to close its 
oldest and largest military bases on foreign soil 
american and philippine officials open talks monday on whether 
the united states will be allowed access to clark air base the 
subic bay naval base and four smaller installations after sept 16 
1991 when the 1947 military bases agreement expires 
because the bases have been the cornerstone of american defense 
of the far east the outcome of the talks will be a central element 
in defining the future us role in east asia 
a new longterm agreement is far from certain 
soviet military retrenchment has led to demands in the us 
congress that the expensive network of foreign bases be trimmed 
filipinos question whether they can be truly independent while 
40000 american service personnel defense department civilians and 
military dependents remain on their soil 
president corazon aquino has refused to say whether she supports 
an extension of the agreement us diplomats and government 
sources say they believe she favors it but has avoided a public 
commitment because the issue is so sensitive 
most filipino politicians who have commented publicly want the 
bases closed next year or phased out by the end of the century 
opposition stiffened after congress cut 96 million from an aid 
package the reagan administration had promised manila in order to 
keep the bases until the agreement expired 
since the end of world war ii filipinos assumed the united 
states wanted to keep the bases at all costs and would pay 
handsomely for the privilege 
in 1988 foreign secretary raul manglapus demanded 2 billion in 
aid but eventually accepted a twoyear package of 962 million 
congressional pressure to reduce defense spending as the soviet 
threat recedes has raised doubts that the bases are worth such a 
price 
defense secretary dick cheney has announced plans to reduce the 
120000 us troops in the far east by 10 to 12 percent over three 
years as the newly prosperous nations of asia assume greater 
responsibility for their own defense 
my sense is that if it looks too testy the united states 
will simply tell the philippines that we will close down paul h 
kreisberg of the carnegie endowment for international peace said 
about the negotiations 
us policymakers and private researchers believe the bases 
still have an important role in projecting american military power 
and maintaining security in the far east 
the american military has been in the philippines since 1898 
when the united states seized the archipelago in the 
spanishamerican war ending 350 years of spanish rule 
it has larger forces elsewhere in asia 64000 troops in japan 
and 43000 in south korea but the philippine bases allow the 
united states great flexibility in crises including those far from 
pacific waters 
nato agreements prohibit the united states from using its 
europeanbased forces outside the alliance area without allied 
permission 
no such restrictions apply in the philippines 
threequarters of the us warships that escorted oil tankers 
through the persian gulf during the iraniraq war were from the 
pacific fleet most were supplied and outfitted at subic 50 miles 
west of manila 
planes from clark and the cubi point naval air station monitor 
shipping lanes and supply the large indian ocean air and naval 
installations at diego garcia 
in a straight military sense the value of the bases declines 
only slightly in a postcold war era said richard fisher a 
heritage foundation policy analyst there will still be a 
requirement to deploy to south korea or potential conflicts in the 
persian gulf 
some functions could be performed on guam saipan and tinian 
more than 1500 miles east but experts say the guam harbor is far 
smaller than subics the islands also lack the skilled labor 
especially ship repairmen available in the philippines 
despite official opposition to foreign forces most east asian 
governments privately support the bases fidel ramos the 
philippine defense secretary said there was little evidence of a 
major reductions in soviet forces in vietnam or in vladivostok 
headquarters of the soviet pacific fleet 
in vietnam the soviet navy uses the usbuilt base at cam ranh 
bay 
the soviets said in january they had reduced air strength at cam 
ranh bay to no more than 10 planes foreign minister nguyen co 
thach of vietnam says all soviet forces will be gone by 1992 
in recent years us officials have played down the soviet 
presence as the reason for maintaining bases philippine bases 
brent scowcroft now president bushs national security adviser 
told a news conference two years ago that trading cam ranh bay for 
subic would be very much in the soviet interest but not 
necessarily in ours the russians dont need it nearly as 
much as we do the philippines 
regional governments fear a drastic reduction in us forces 
would cause such nations as china japan vietnam and india to 
expand their forces 
without a persuasive us presence there will be a power 
vacuum which other powers would scramble to fill said lee hsien 
loong singapores deputy defense minister 
such geopolitical concerns mean less than money and national 
pride in the introspective philippines 
most surveys indicate supporters of the bases outnumber 
opponents but filipinos in growing numbers believe the american 
presence infringes national sovereignty 
the installations pump an estimated 1 billion into the economy 
however and more than 270000 filipinos depend on them for a 
livelihood 
those people who say we have alternatives to the bases have to 
prove they can replace the considerable support given by the us 
facilities to the city said mayor richard gordon of olongapo 
home of the subic base 
opposition to the bases stems from complex oftencontradictory 
views of the united states which ruled the philippines from 1898 
to 1946 
admiration of american culture borders on obsession among 
filipinos the most westernized asians but many believe this has 
created a psychological dependence that inhibits national 
development 
the philippine military relies almost entirely on the united 
states for external defense its navy often turns to the americans 
for help in air and sea rescues us air force meteorologists warn 
their filipino counterparts of approaching typhoons 
on the other side critics claim the bases encourage 
prostitution the sleazy bars and nightclubs of olongapo and 
angeles home of clark air base serve as evidence 
the whole bases campaign is a quest for finding out who we 
are said socorro diokno chairman of the antibases coalition 
can the filipino stand on his feet without having to rely on 
america 
dependence on the united states was dramatized in december when 
american f4 phantom jets from clark flew air cover for government 
forces during a coup attempt 
the planes never fired a shot but their presence stopped rebel 
air attacks on military and government buildings including the 
presidential palace 
last year mrs aquino appointed a committee to study 
alternative uses for the bases if no new agreement was reached 
proposals include converting clark to a civilian airport and 
establishing a commercial ship repair facility at subic 
businessmen in olongapo and angeles are skeptical 
we firmly believe that any conversion plan regarding 
alternative uses of the bases entails huge costs and implementation 
is doubtful the angeles chamber of commerce and industry in a 
statement 
