inside the luxury hotel was a 
conference on tourism and crime in rio just outside two 
tourists were mugged 
men with shotguns hold up airport buses valuables are stolen at 
the beach from hotel rooms 
police booths sprout in every block cariocas as rios 
residents are called have special devices on their cars that cut 
off the fuel supply when a thief has driven a few blocks 
crime always has infested rios slums but now it is common on 
the glitzy tourist beaches and the streets where money lives 
cariocas have little affinity for the police or justice system 
and often settle disputes themselves increasingly guns are the 
arbiters of choice 
not long ago antonio enrique de oliveira sighted down the 
barrel of his new 38caliber pistol and squeezed off a shot 
thats my law the husky 26yearold mechanic said as the 
report echoed off the hills overlooking the vast poor suburb of 
nova iguacu its the only law that works in rio anymore 
death squads generally offduty policemen fed up with the 
inefficient courts and turnstile justice make another kind of law 
they simply kill known criminals or suspects often for pay from 
merchants 
among reasons for the crime wave are poverty rarity of 
punishment the example of official corruption inflation that 
reached nearly 5000 percent and forced harsh economic measures 
and an everwidening gap between rich and poor 
the top 1 percent of brazils 150 million people have as much 
wealth as the bottom 50 percent 
police statistics say homicides in metropolitain rio rose from 
2924 in 1983 to 7654 last year 
residents and religious leaders say most killings dont get into 
the records a city police official who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said there were nearly 20000 in metropolitan rio last 
year 
crime has never been this bad were fighting a guerrilla 
war said helio vigio a police inspector for 20 years 
a sociologist helio jaguaribe said the elite and the 
establishment can no longer control tensions between rich and poor 
crime is now seen by the poor as social retribution 
gun sales icreased from 15520 in 1987 to 22872 in 1989 
cariocas bar their windows and buy burglar alarms and watch dogs 
neighbors often band together to hire armed guards 
my sales are doubling every three months said mauro cesar 
martins who displays eight models of 38 caliber revolvers in his 
downtown sporting goods store people trust only their gun for 
protection can you blame them 
police say thousands of automatic weapons smuggled from paraguay 
and bolivia are bought and sold in illegal gun markets 
for years violent crime was largely confined to rios north 
zone a poor densely populated area far from the beaches of the 
wealthy south zone 
automatic weapons abound in the north zone gang wars end in 
massacres 
citizens carry pistols in their shorts children as young as 5 
run cocaine to customers in affluent neighborhoods 
bodies are dumped in the streets every day sometimes outside 
police stations one sunday in january 10 were found in a group 
shot through the head a month later a record 57 corpses turned up 
in rio in a single weekend 
gang leaders establish personal fiefdoms in the favelas or 
hillside shantytowns and organize residents into defense units 
the slums are becoming armed fortresses of urban warfare 
said lt eide trindade director of rios task force on organized 
crime 
on drug raids in the hills you run into nests of machine 
gunners when they open fire its like walking into lightning 
city police poorly equipped trained and paid are no match for 
the wellarmed criminals they are sent into the streets without 
nightsticks holsters or bulletproof vests and must buy their own 
uniforms 
each officer is given six bullets every three months they 
patrol in 13yearold volkswagen beetles which often have broken 
radios 
rio has 12000 municipal police and 27000 state police in a 
metropolitan area of 105 million people 
death squads which first appeared in the 1950s are growing 
with the crime wave community leaders say they have more than 
2000 members compared with 500 two years ago 
a police inquiry made public in april said the chiefs of 15 
death squads in greater rio were active state policemen 
the death squads are in complete control of the people if 
anyone sees a murder and opens his mouth hes as good as dead 
said azuleika rodrigues president of the federation of 
neighborhood associations in nova iguacu 
low pay causes police strikes and corruption a rookie cop earns 
the equivalent of 100 a month and a topranking inspector 335 
you have to be a parttime crook or mobster to eat or have 
your teeth fixed said officer jose quimonte 33 who works 48 
hours a week for 188 
there is temptation for officers to break the law and little 
incentive for them to enforce it 
police say lawbreakers are encouraged by a slow understaffed 
judicial system and the belief that criminals will get light 
sentences or go free 
if you bring someone in chances are that if hes rich 
