<TEXT>
the marapicu cemetery in the impoverished 
baixada fluminense suburbs of rio de janeiro has been a burial 
ground for victims of death squads for nearly 30 years police 
officials admit knowing this but have neither undertaken an 
investigation nor explained their failure to do so todd lewan 
visited the graveyard 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the dead have no names in marapicu 
cemetery 
no one knows who they were or where they came from death squads 
killed them that is all anyone remembers 
sebastiao fernandez da rocha a sparrowlike man of 72 buries 
them at first it made him sad to think he was the last to see the 
victims he was gentle in lowering the younger ones 
after 17 years pity no longer hangs on his features he is a 
gaunt old man with thick calluses raised by the hoe and shovel the 
bodies mean little more to him now than the dirt he throws over 
them 
each morning before dawn rocha begins a twohour walk to work 
on a winding road through one of brazils most lawless regions the 
baixada fluminense 
orange groves and cotton once flourished in the baixadas 
lowlands but the the plantations were divided into plots 30 years 
ago and sold to squatters poverty is everywhere machine guns make 
the law death is judgment 
when rocha arrives in queimados which means burned ones he 
whistles into the open doors of the shacks of two young helpers 
they walk up the red dirt road together to the cemetery on the hill 
so close are the graves that they nearly touch hundreds of 
white stone crosses bearing painted numbers jut crookedly from 
the rocky ground there are no headstones 
the task on this morning presuming death squads attacked again 
in the night was to dig six graves when that was done rocha and 
the young men sat in the shade painting crosses white while they 
waited 
in the heat of the midday sun a dust cloud rose on the ridge a 
morgue van rolled up rocha put on his straw hat and went to it 
the barefoot youths followed 
lots of meat today said the driver a big sweaty man he 
threw the rear doors open 
inside were the bodies of eight men and a small girl in a sun 
dress who had been shot in the stomach some of the mens faces 
were unrecognizable nearly blown away 
rocha went into a small office near the gate wrote the number 9 
in a ledger and returned they pulled the corpses out like sacks of 
beans and dropped them into plywood boxes the boxes keep wild dogs 
from digging bodies up 
the young men carried the boxes down the slope while rocha dug 
three more holes 
fifty yards away was a single grave with flowers blooming on it 
thats my son rocha said i found his body about 10 
minutes walk from here on my way in one morning they broke his 
neck and spine dont know why no one ever finds out why they 
die 
rocha thrust the shovel into the earth he was wheezing ribs 
pressing against a torn blue shirt 
he was 15 the old man said his name was luis luis 
enrique 
he and the others worked quickly silently to cover the graves 
only the rasp of their hoes on the crude coffins interfered with 
the sound of a rising wind 
when it was done they went out through the black gates and sat 
under a mango tree on a bluff drinking rum from tin cups 
will there be more today old man one of the young ones 
asked 
yes 
it is terrible isnt it 
rocha grunted this is the way things are he said i 
remember a proverb the blame lies not only with the ax but the 
tree as well yes that is the proverb 
the young men nodded and had another pull of rum 
