<TEXT>
a federal appeals court decision striking down a 
key insider trading rule deals a sharp blow to enforcement of wall 
streets crime of the 1980s lawyers say 
the ruling by the 2nd us circuit court of appeals in new york 
also renewed calls for congress to pass a law precisely defining 
insider trading which refers to the use of information not 
publicly available to buy and sell securities 
this should put a little bit of fear into people who want to 
see a very strong enforcement program harvey l pitt a top 
securities lawyer who helped draft failed 1987 insider trading 
legislation said thursday 
it demonstrates again why the securities and exchange 
commission would be better off if they had a definition of insider 
trading that was blessed by the congress said pitt who 
represented ivan boesky the speculator who settled insider trading 
charges in 1987 
the appeals court wednesday overturned the conviction of former 
stockbroker robert chestman found guilty of insider trading using 
fourthhand information about the pending takeover of a supermarket 
chain in 1986 
in a 30 decision the court ruled there was no proof chestman 
knew that information about the takeover of waldbaum inc which 
trickled down to him through a family chain was confidential 
also the panel by a 21 vote slammed the door on a key 
securities exchange act provision that makes any trading using 
confidential information a crime even if the trader isnt 
violating a fiduciary responsibility to the company involved 
that provision known as rule 14e3 was adopted by the 
securities and exchange commission in 1980 to broaden its attack on 
insider trading 
the government has relied on fraud rules and case law to 
prosecute insider trading which became a household term during the 
boom years last decade via fraud rings run by figures such as 
boesky and investment banker martin siegel 
i think its a very substantial blow to both the justice 
department and the secs enforcement efforts if the decision 
stands said robert l plotz a former assistant us attorney 
who prosecuted the chestman case now in private practice 
sec enforement director william mclucas declined to comment on 
the decisions impact saying the commission was disappointed but 
still reviewing the case the government could ask for a full 
appeals court review or appeal to the supreme court 
lawyers said the decision erodes some power investigators had 
gained over insider trading they said without a statutory 
definition the government was leaving the door open to future 
cases that will chip away at its authority 
they ought to define it as a matter of criminal law said 
don buchwald who defended former wall street journal reporter r 
foster winans in a 1985 insider trading case fairness requires 
you have a definition especially if youre going to put people in 
jail 
but congress repeatedly has resisted efforts to define insider 
trading on the theory that pinpointing illegal behavior would leave 
loopholes for abuse a lack of consensus about a law also has been 
cited 
chestman was convicted by a jury on 31 counts of fraud last year 
and spent about 10 months in federal prison before his release 
wednesday 
two congressional aides to committees that oversee the sec said 
it was too soon to tell whether the chestman case would resurrect a 
movement to define insider trading the most recent attempt was in 
1988 when congress stiffened insider trading penalties 
the appeals court nullified rule 14e3 which allowed 
prosecutors broad leeway to chase insider trading in a corporate 
takeovers a situation that often caused a target companys stock 
price to jump the rule was designed to attack wrongdoing that 
didnt necessarily involve a company directly 
other sec rules already made clear that individuals with 
responsibilities to a company including employees management 
directors lawyers and other advisers could not trade on 
marketsensitive information about it 
columbia university law professor john c coffee jr said that 
under the added rule it was enough to show that the individual 
had reason to believe the information came from a source either 
within the bidder or the target 
the rule was used in key wall street civil and criminal fraud 
cases including the original case against former junk bond 
financier michael milken though not in his plea bargain admitting 
securities and tax fraud last month 
besides the rule 14e3 question the appeals court ruled that 
chestman heard no more than family gossip when the husband of 
the daughter of the sister of waldbaums family patriarch told him 
the company would be sold 
</TEXT>
