<TEXT>
cosmetics giant avon products inc is under 
pressure from its shareholders to either drop a key takeover 
defense or put it to a vote 
shareholders approved two nonbinding proposals thursday at 
their annual meeting relating to the companys share rights plans 
commonly known as poison pills that can make unsolicited buyout 
bids prohibitively expensive 
the company has been in turmoil for more than a year as it found 
buyers for its health care business and a fragrance company while 
improving the profitability of the direct selling business on which 
it was founded 
it struck a deal with a large investor group that resulted in 
putting two of the groups representatives on its board and the 
formation of a committee to explore the companys alternatives 
which include more asset sales a recapitalization or outright sale 
of the company 
avon management opposed both shareholder proposals on its share 
rights plans and favors keeping the company independent while 
pursuing its own plan for sales and earnings growth by focusing on 
direct selling 
one proposal urged the company to either drop the rights plan or 
submit it to a shareholder vote the second urged a vote on the 
plan 
both passed with nearly 254 million shares in favor more than 
167 million opposed and more than 167 million abstaining 
the united shareholders association a washington dcbased 
advocacy group said it was behind one of the proposals 
avons management would be foolish not to implement proposals 
that so clearly expressed the will of the shareholders said 
association director ralph whitworth 
in trading on the new york stock exchange avon fell 75 cents a 
share to 3637 
the shareholders also elected four directors to the avon board 
including two nominees representing the investor group chartwell 
associates lp chartwell owns 12 percent of avons voting stock and 
had planned to run a slate of candidates for the four open seats on 
the 11member board 
but under a settlement reached in late march avon agreed to 
support two chartwell nominees along with two incumbent directors 
for the four seats that were up for election those nominees were 
elected thursday 
in addition avon agreed to set up a committee to consider ways 
of boosting value for avon stockholders the committee will include 
four avon directors and executives and the two new board members 
from chartwell m anthony fisher and marc leland 
the settlement also called for the appointment of john p 
rochon a principal in the chartwell group as an avon advisor once 
he resigns as vice chairman of mary kay cosmetics avons 
dallasbased rival 
james e preston chairman and chief executive of avon said 
negotiations are continuing on how much rochon will be paid and 
said there was no financial settlement at all with chartwell 
preston said he did not feel avon had a hostile relationship 
with chartwell which also includes members of the fisher real 
estate family of new york and gordon p getty the oil heir 
avon recently voted to lower the threshold of its rights plan to 
make one element of it effective when an outsider buys 125 percent 
of its stock rather than the previous 20 percent 
the action came after chartwell disclosed it had raised its 
voting stake in avon to 12 percent from 75 percent chartwell won 
a court order against the avon board on the threshold increase 
avon has appealed 
preston told about 400 people gathered for the meeting at the 
museum of natural history that avon was making progress by focusing 
on its core business 
he said avon would push ahead with plans to sell its 60 percent 
interest in avon japan by the end of the year an earlier proposal 
to sell the stake to tokyobased friends of freesia ltd for 450 
million fell through 
asked why avon was getting out of japan while other companies 
were scrambling to get in preston said avon japans market niche 
is in danger of being eroded by bigger companies and would require 
large investments to defend 
we are better off selling that business and cashing out today 
and reinvesting in markets where we can grow faster he said 
