<TEXT>
higherthanexpected first quarter earnings for 
the big three automakers may mean they are coming out of a severe 
recession analysts say 
earnings reported thursday by general motors corp and ford 
motor co combined with those released tuesday by chrysler corp 
were down 64 percent compared with the same three months of last 
year 
the decline fell short of wall street analysts predictions of a 
cumulative drop of more than 75 percent 
its almost like the auto industry was going through its own 
inventory recession in the first quarter and in a sense its 
coming out of its own selfcreated recession in the second 
quarter analyst david healy of barclaysbzw of new york said 
analyst scott merlis of morgan stanley amp co said signs of 
recovery although welcome were relative 
when you go from a depression to a recession its a nice 
improvement he said 
each of the big three laid part of the blame for lower profits 
on severe production cuts they instituted in january to help reduce 
inventories which had built to a high 90sellingday level at the 
end of last year 
the production reduction coupled with increased incentives 
knocked inventories down to the 65day range considered good for 
this time of year 
but the twopronged attack combined with economic and labor 
problems overseas ate into profits 
fords overseas earnings were hammered by strikes in europe and 
economic problems in brazil 
i think we are going to see a material drag on fords earnings 
from brazil in the second quarter largely because there has been no 
production there since the 15th of march analyst john kirnan of 
kidder peabody amp co said 
on that day ford shut down its autolatina plant after the 
government froze most savings in an attempt halt inflation that was 
running at an annual rate of more than 4000 percent 
the plant is back in operation but it will take time for it to 
gear up production to preshutdown levels 
gm which declined to detail regional operations said it set 
record overseas profits but also had been hurt in brazil although 
to a smaller extent than ford 
gm spokesman terry sullivan said the effects of brazils 
economic problems may show up later for gm 
chrysler has few overseas operations 
