an agreement by opec members to jointly curb 
overproduction wont provide a quick fix for the oil market where 
prices continue to sag analysts say 
in fact the markets initial reaction to the accord reached 
thursday was to push prices decisively lower in fairly heavy 
trading 
the market may have been looking for more than opec was 
willing to give said peter beutel an energy analyst for elders 
futures inc in new york it came out looking like another of 
these vaguely unsatisfying agreements 
the cartels 13 members came out of a twoday emergency session 
with an accord to cut total output by 1455 million barrels a day 
for the next three months 
the organization of petroleum exporting countries hope the 
cutback will help prices recover to the groups minimum reference 
price of 18 a barrel set in november 
north sea brent blend the most widely traded international 
crude oil fell to 1590 a barrel in london late thursday after 
opecs anouncement that was down 55 cents from late wednesday 
