<TEXT>
environmentalists are praising the senate 
agriculture committee for toughening conservation efforts on farms 
through the 1990 farm bill 
its a major step forward ken cook of the center for 
resource economics said thursday after the committee finished work 
on the conservation section of legislation that will set 
agriculture policy for the next five years 
were very pleased with the way the committee has responded to 
environmental concerns said cook who lobbied for tougher 
standards 
committee chairman patrick leahy dvt said the bill is good 
for both the environment and farmers this new title 
significantly strengthens the conservation provisions of current 
law he said 
leahy said the 1985 farm bill signaled a new attitude in 
congress about the important role our farmers play in preserving 
the environment they also set the standard by which the 1990 farm 
bill will be judged 
most of the provisions were approved wednesday but one of the 
stickiest the section on wetlands was passed out of committee 
thursday 
it actually eases up on farmers in some ways 
current law strips a farmer of his or her federal subsidies if 
wetlands are drained and planted with crops 
if the new measure becomes law violators would be fined 750 to 
10000 and required to restore the wetland the farmer would be 
removed from federal crop programs after a second offense 
the farmer would have his record expunged after 10 years and 
return to firsttime violator status if wetlands are drained again 
sen kent conrad dnd voted against the wetlands measure 
because he felt farmers sometimes make innocent mistakes and the 
potential for abuse by regulators under the legislation was too 
high 
the new measure also allows drainage of land that has been 
extensively farmed but still has wetland characteristics if the 
drainage would have minimal effect on wetland values 
most of the time a farmer would have to restore another piece 
of property to prevent net wetland loss 
a provision that toughens current wetland policy outlaws the 
draining of land if the intention is to make it available for 
planting at some time under the law enacted in 1985 a farmer has 
to actually plant on the drained land to be a violator 
enforcement of federal wetland policy is conducted by the soil 
conservation service and the agricultural stabilization and 
conservation service fish and wildlife service agents make reports 
when they see lands in use that are supposed to remain in a wet 
condition 
wetlands are important not only as habitats for wildlife but as 
natural filters for pollutants only about half the countrys 
original wetlands still exist and the government is fighting to 
save them 
conservation measures adopted by the committee wednesday 
included 
enrollment of at least 40 million acres by 1995 in a program 
that pays farmers not to plant in order to protect highly erodible 
land marginal pasturelands windbreaks and vegetation planted for 
wildlife 
payments to farmers who enroll in a new program to reduce water 
contamination by cutting back on fertilizers and chemicals that 
cause pollution 
technical assistance from the agriculture department to help 
farmers meet state and federal environmental standards 
purchase of wetlands from farmers 
requirements that farmers keep records of pesticides they use 
assistance to states that want to protect farms from being 
converted to other uses 
the chairman of the house agriculture committee rep kika de la 
garza dtexas introduced conservation legislation thursday with 
many provisions similar to the senate bill hearings on it will be 
held later 
</TEXT>
