<TEXT>
the soviet union has emerged as a stunning new 
market for broilers and may edge out japan this year as the 
traditional no 1 foreign market for us poultry according to 
agriculture department analysts 
more than 110 million pounds of broiler leg quarters were sold 
to the soviet union recently by us companies a sale worth an 
estimated 50 million 
the soviets began buying us broilers last fall for the first 
time in years according to the departments economic research 
service the 1989 sales involved about 26 million pounds 
usda economist larry witucki said in a telephone interview 
thursday that moscow has bought around 260 million pounds of us 
broilers so far in calendar 1990 those could have a value in the 
range of 100 million to 150 million 
i would say the soviets are going to surpass the japanese 
this year witucki said the japanese market is growing but 
not that fast 
the soviet union has been buying us grain for years and is 
apparently is committed to remain a major buyer for the long haul 
can broiler producers expect similar demand from chickenhungry 
kremlin leaders 
witucki said the soviet broiler market is characterized by large 
potential and large uncertainty its hard to tell at the moment 
what may happen he said 
