strong said the report which was written prior to the recent 
new sale to the soviets 
it added although exports could decline to mexico and canada 
where production is expected to increase the ussr and some 
eastern european countries will become a major new market 
in a related report the departments foreign agricultural 
service says the soviet union and eastern europe represent 
substantial market opportunities for us meat and poultry 
exporters 
if goals for meat consumption are to be met domestic and 
imported supplies will have to increase a main thrust will be in 
rising demand for improved livestock breeding and technology 
the report said average soviet citizens spend 50 percent to 60 
percent of their takehome salary of 200 rubles per month 330 
for food 
even so strong demand for meat products persists the 
report said during the opening of the first mcdonalds food 
franchise restaurant in the ussr hundreds of muscovites line 
up to pay three rubles and 75 kopecks about onethird of a days 
wage to purchase a big mac 
meat consumption in the soviet union includes about 44 percent 
beef 34 percent pork 5 percent sheep lamb and other meat and 17 
percent poultry the report said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
thailand is one of the few developing 
countries with a substantial food surplus says an agriculture 
department report and that is important to us farmers 
in the last 20 years the southeast asian country of 56 million 
people has established itself as a strong competitor in world feed 
grain markets the report said 
recent years have shown thailand to be the worlds largest rice 
exporter the fifthlargest corn exporter and an important exporter 
of sorghum all commodities that rank highly as us exports 
but thailand also is boosting livestock output according to the 
report by sara j schwartz and douglas h brooks of the 
departments economic research service looking ahead to the turn 
of the century that raises some possibilities 
under a moderate growth scenario developed for the study 
