<TEXT>
the new york stock exchange wants to fine the 
fallen brokerage drexel burnham lambert inc 25 million in 
connection with securities fraud and other crimes sources said 
friday 
the fine would be the largest ever imposed on a securities firm 
but whether the big board ever would collect is unclear drexel is 
liquidating after its parent company filed for bankruptcy court 
protection in february 
the nyse has the ability to levy fines against member firms and 
executives for violating exchange rules and securities laws the 
exchange has been mulling whether to fine drexel since the firm 
pleaded guilty to six felony crimes and agreed to pay 650 million 
in government penalties last year 
the nyse also is said to be considering brining separate 
disciplinary proceedings against drexel chief executive frederick 
h joseph and other top officers of the firm 
those charges would be in connection with the activities of the 
firm and its former junk bond leader michael milken who pleaded 
guilty last month to six separate felonies and agreed to pay 600 
million in penalties 
nyse spokesman richard torrenzano declined comment on whether 
the nyse was pursuing charges against drexel but he said drexel 
is the biggest regulatory problem by a member firm that weve had 
in the 200year history of the new york stock exchange 
the possible fine first was reported in todays editions of the 
wall street journal people with knowledge of the proceedings who 
asked not to be named confirmed the report 
in a statement drexel defended its compliance mechanisms 
saying its procedures were as good or better than other firms on 
the street and its transgressions chiefly involved verbal 
agreements that werent disclosed to the firm 
its clear that there were things that went wrong but the 
firm and its shareholderemployees have already paid dearly for 
them drexel said any further penalties would be added 
unnecessary punishment for creditors and shareholders and could be 
viewed simply as piling on 
we understand the stock exchanges need to project an image of 
being a strong regulator it said however that should be 
balanced with a sense of fairness in evaluting the companys and 
managements behavior 
the journal report said that the big board has stepped up its 
investigation of drexel in recent weeks and has subpoenaed several 
individuals to testify about drexels and milkens behavior 
the charges against joseph and other drexel officials that are 
being considered were said to include failure to properly supervise 
milken and others such charges could be important because they 
carry possible expulsion from the securities industry 
under stock exchange procedures drexel could challenge any 
sanction before an nyse hearing board the firm later could appeal 
any ruling to the nyse board of directors the securities and 
exchange commission or a federal appeals court 
