<TEXT>
a weaker than expected employment report has 
stopped the drive for higher interest rates and should help the 
treasury find buyers for its quarterly sale of notes and bonds this 
week economists say 
fears that the economy was expanding too rapidly and threatening 
to drive inflation higher had gripped the credit markets in recent 
weeks driving longterm bond yields above 9 percent for the first 
time in nearly a year 
economic data in the past few weeks had supported that bearish 
scenario the consumer price index rose at an annual rate of 85 
percent in the first quarter the fastest rate since the 
inflationary spiral at the start of the 1980s 
orders for durable goods a key benchmark for the economy 
surged 67 percent in march and purchasing managers reported that 
the manufacturing economy expanded for the first time in 11 months 
in april 
fridays jobs report from the labor department went a long way 
toward dissolving those fears however and should keep longterm 
rates below 9 percent economists say 
the nations unemployment rate ticked up to 54 percent in april 
from 52 percent in march the number of jobs grew by a slight 
64000 and would have shown a small decline if not for the 
temporary hiring of census workers factory payrolls fell by 
22000 the 12th drop in the last 13 months 
the best you can say about the manufacturing sector is its 
stopped shrinking said david h resler chief economist at 
nomura securities international inc 
as for the economy in general maybe its not on the brink of 
recession but its certainly not growing vigorously either he 
added 
mitchell held chief economist at smith barney harris upham amp 
co said the figures were especially encouraging in showing a 
continued slowdown in the growth of service sector employment that 
sector had been particularly resistant to the federal reserves 
effort to slow the economy 
whats more average hourly earnings rose a mere 03 percent in 
april or 3 cents to 995 an hour despite the 50 cent hike in the 
minimum wage to 385 an hour 
all those things together are really encouraging held said 
they should dispel worries that the fed might have to engineer a 
rise in interest rates to keep the economy and inflation in check 
the fed is probably going to keep policy steady he 
predicted 
manufacturers have reported greater price pressure for labor and 
materials in the first quarter as well as an increase in their 
selling prices said john d walter economist for dow corning 
corp and director of the national association of business 
economists industry survey 
nevertheless walter said consumer sticker shock and restrained 
growth in the money supply will cool inflation from the first 
quarter pace while strong capital spending is raising industrys 
capacity 
he sees the economy in a modest upturn with growth waffling 
between 1 percent and 3 percent over the next year in short the 
softlanding scenario of restrained growth without recession is 
still on track walter said 
that would be good news for a market that has to digest the 
treasurys auctions of 305 billion in three and 10year notes 
and 30year bonds from tuesday through thursday its also good 
news for the government 
resler estimates the employment report will enable the treasury 
to price the auctions at least an eighth of a percentage point 
lower than it otherwise would have say between 8 percent and 9 
percent for the long bond instead of 99lsqb percent 
that would save 250 million over the life of the three issues 
a nice little windfall for the treasury 
held says longterm bonds should settle into a trading range of 
8 percent to 9 percent down from a widely perceived 8 percent to 
9 percent before friday 
