<TEXT>
the nations most powerful labor union 
reached agreement friday to cut its work week to 35 hours 
signalling a broad move toward more leisure time for workers in one 
of the worlds richest countries 
fridays pact worked out during tense allnight negotiations 
with an employers organization immediately affects about 700000 
factory workers in the state of badenwuerttemberg 
the precedent is expected to be followed as the ig metall 
metalworkers union negotiates contracts for the rest of the country 
west germans already have six weeks of vacation each year a 
sprinkling of about 10 holidays and legally guaranteed work breaks 
on the job 
for years the mighty ig metall union which negotiates 
contracts for 4 million workers in the metalworking automobile 
and related industries has demanded a reduction to 35 hours the 
current work week is 37 hours compared with 40 hours in 1985 
our dream goal has been reached said union president franz 
steinkuehler in frankfurt we wanted time and money and we got 
both 
the cut will come in two stages to 36 hours in april 1993 and 
35 hours in october 1995 while the agreement also calls for 6 
percent pay hike spread out over 12 months 
in frankfurt the printers union immediately said that it also 
will be seeking to cut hours to 35 a week 
i expect this compromise probably to be adopted nationwide 
said joerg barzcynski ig metall spokesman 
ig metall had staged warning strikes involving more than 300000 
workers and temporarily halting production at a few hundred west 
german plants this week 
steinkuehler promised a round of strikes to keep up pressure on 
employers in other parts of the country to reach agreements 
the compromise was reached in the key west german industrial 
area around the city of stuttgart which houses car and truck 
manufacturer daimlerbenz among other major companies 
west german politicians reacted critically to the compromise 
economics minister helmut haussman termed it a false signal 
ahead of german unification 
the unions are artifically restricting our most important 
production factor he said 
otto lambsdorff head of the coalition partner free democrats 
called the accord on the 35hour work week a speculative 
agreement about the future 
west german employers organizations repeatedly have said the 
trend toward less work and higher pay combined with the nations 
massive social security net is driving more businesses to cheaper 
countries in southern europe 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

