<TEXT>
trade ministers from three continents 
reported today they had failed to resolve several disputes that are 
threatening to scuttle an ambitious effort to reform the global 
trading system 
officials from the united states japan the 12nation european 
community and canada said at the conclusion of three days of talks 
that they had a frank exchange of views but remained far apart in 
many areas especially on the contentious issue of how to end 
expensive farm subsidies 
us trade representative carla hills said the talks were in the 
home stretch but she conceded that much work needed to be done 
the ministers did report some progress on bridging differences 
on some lowlevel issues such as how trade disputes should be 
handled but said sharp differences remained in the two key areas of 
agriculture subsidies and barriers to textile imports 
hills spoke at a sundrenched news conference held on the edge 
of a golf course at the resort where the talks were held 
the bush administration is counting on an agreement by the end 
of this year to lower americas huge trade deficit by expanding 
export opportunities for us farmers and businesses 
the american side is pushing to eliminate expensive farm export 
subsidies to dismantle barriers to trade in services such as 
banking and to crack down on copyright and patent piracy estimated 
to cost american firms 60 billion annually 
officials said they aim to draw up the general outline of an 
agreement during a bargaining session in geneva in late july and 
then work toward a final agreement in december 
the talks held under the auspices of the 97nation general 
agreement on tariffs and trade or gatt are known as the uruguay 
round of free trade talks for the country where they were launched 
in 1986 
us trade representative carla hills who selected her home 
state of california for the meeting expressed satisfaction with 
what she termed a quite constructive session 
a senior us official briefing reporters on condition of 
anonymity said the talks produced no major breakthroughs although 
he said they helped define the opposing positions 
all sides reported that the biggest dispute how to put an end 
to tradedistorting farm subsidies remained far from resolution 
as the european community held fast to its desire to protect a 
subsidy system for its network of small farms 
frans andriessen trade minister for the european community 
termed the discussions frank often a diplomatic code word for 
unfruitful talks 
many third world nations who were not represented at the napa 
meetings are battling the us proposals especially on lowering 
trade barriers for service industries they contend that their 
fledgling service companies should be protected from foreign 
concerns invading their markets 
canadian trade minister john crosbie said he would put the 
chances of successfully wrapping up the negotiations in december at 
little better than 50 percent 
but he said he was still hopeful because the consequences of 
failure are so horrific the alternative is the law of the 
jungle and only the largest beasts will survive and they wont 
survive very well 
hills sounded a similar theme contending that without a 
strengthened trade agreement both industrial and third world 
nations would suffer declining standards of living as trade flows 
contracted behind protectionist walls 
the administration is having to wage a dual war seeking to 
convince the europeans and developing countries to drop their 
opposition to the free trade proposals while fighting off efforts 
in congress to erect barriers protecting threatened us industries 
congress must approve any final agreement and the outcome of 
that debate is far from certain already special interest groups 
representing the textile industry and peanut and sugar growers are 
working to build congressional opposition to changes in gatt rules 
that would strip them of trade protections they now enjoy 
</TEXT>
