<TEXT>
new evidence from april employment figures of an 
unexpectedly weak economy triggered a furious rally friday in the 
bond market sending interest rates sharply lower 
the bond buying binge offered a marked contrast to the gloom 
that depressed the market for much of the month of april hammering 
bond prices and pushing longterm interest rates bove 9 percent for 
the first time since last may 
the treasurys benchmark 30year bond climbed 1 points or 
1625 for every 1000 face amount in one of the years biggest 
rallies 
its yield which falls when prices rise tumbled to 881 percent 
from 897 percent late thursday 
analysts said the governments report that the unemployment rate 
rose to 54 percent in april from 52 percent in march was the 
catalyst for the big price rally 
what caught most bond traders interest was the report of a 
measly net gain of 64000 jobs in april well below what analysts 
had expected 
elliott platt fixedincome research director for donaldson 
lufkin amp jenrette securities corp said if the addition of 78000 
temporary census workers were excluded from the numbers jobs would 
have fallen by 14000 last month he said analysts expected an 
increase of 150000 jobs not counting the census workers for april 
in addition he said wage inflation was up 03 percent in april 
when many analysts were expecting 05 percent growth partly due to 
the april 1 boost in the minimum wage but the minimum wage 
increase had minimal impact on overall wage growth officials 
indicated 
this report indicates a lot of weakness in the economy people 
had thought the economy was stronger with a much deeper inflation 
problem platt said 
the bond market benefits from a slow economic growth and low 
inflation because credit demand generally falls off during sluggish 
periods and allows interest rates to decline 
rising inflation and rapid growth on the other hand erodes the 
value of fixedincome securities such as notes and bonds and could 
prompt the federal reserve to encourage higher interest rates 
there is nothing the bond market likes better than bad news 
said robert brusca chief economist for nikko securities 
international 
he said the bond market had overreacted over the past few months 
to indications that the economy was growing rapidly and inflation 
was accelerating 
the market rally could not have been timed any better for the 
treasury department which is planning to sell 305 billion in new 
securities next week barring a sudden reversal in market sentiment 
early next week the government may find buyers at lower yields 
than had been expected only a few days ago 
in the secondary market for treasury bonds prices of shortterm 
governments rose point intermediate maturities climbed by 
between 1116 point and a full point and longterm issues advanced 
1 points according to telerate inc the financial information 
service 
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of 10 in the 
price of a bond with a 1000 face value 
the shearson lehman hutton daily treasury bond index which 
measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with 
maturities of a year or longer rose 915 to 114076 
in the taxexempt market the bond buyer index of 40 actively 
traded municipal bonds climbed 716 point to 89 the average yield 
to maturity fell to 768 percent from 772 percent 
yields on threemonth treasury bills fell to 800 percent as the 
discount lost 10 basis points to 775 percent yields on sixmonth 
bills fell to 823 percent as the discount dropped 16 basis points 
to 781 percent yields on oneyear bills fell to 839 percent as 
the discount fell 22 basis points to 782 percent 
a basis point is onehundredth of a percentage point the yield 
is the annualized return on an investment in a treasury bill the 
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face 
value which is paid at maturity 
the federal funds rate the interest rate banks charge each 
other on overnight loans was quoted at 8 316 percent unchanged 
from late thursday 
