<TEXT>
trade ministers representing the largest 
industrial countries reported friday they had failed to resolve 
major disputes blocking an ambitious effort to overhaul the global 
trading system 
speaking at the end of a threeday negotiating session 
officials of the united states japan the 12nation european 
community and canada said sharp differences still remained over 
such issues as a us demand for the elimination of costly 
agricultural barriers 
us trade representative carla hills and the leaders of the 
other delegations sought to portray the talks in a positive light 
saying the discussions were useful in highlighting areas of 
disagreement and providing momentum to resolving disputes 
canadian trade minister john crosbie praised the discussions for 
turning the heat up in the fouryear effort to liberalize the 
rules governing world trade 
the officials said progress has been made toward narrowing 
differences in certain lowerlevel issues such as how trade 
disputes are handled 
but they were unable to point to any breakthroughs in the major 
areas of dispute including agriculture and barriers erected by the 
united states and other industrial countries to textile imports 
with time running out on the fouryear effort to reform the 
global trading system hills said the negotiators would appeal to 
president bush and other leaders at the sevennation economic 
summit in july to supply a political push to break the 
stalemates 
hills and crosbie participated at the closing press conference 
with japanese trade minister kabun muto and frans andriessen top 
trade negotiator for the european community 
they spoke to reporters on the patio of a posh resort in the 
heart of california wine country a site selected by hills a 
california native 
the talks were intended to provide guidance so that lower level 
negotiators would be able to come up with at least the outline of a 
final agreement during talks scheduled for late july in geneva 
hills said she remained confident that with intensive effort 
such a document could be produced in coming weeks 
the bush administration has made a successful conclusion of the 
complex negotiations which are scheduled to end in december its 
no 1 trade priority 
the administration believes the freer trade that would result 
would lower americas huge trade deficit by expanding overseas 
sales by american farmers and businesses 
us negotiators are pushing to eliminate all tradedistorting 
farm subsidies to dismantle barriers to trade in services such as 
banking and to crack down on copyright and patent piracy estimated 
to cost american firms 60 billion annually 
the talks being held under the auspices of the 97nation 
general agreement on tariffs and trade are known as the uruguay 
round for the country where they were launched in 1986 
the united states has proposed a 10year phaseout of the farm 
subsidies estimating it would boost exports for more efficient 
american farmers by 11 billion annually 
but the european community seeking to protect its wide network 
of small family farms has refused to budge from its opposition 
many third world nations which were not represented at the napa 
meetings are battling the us proposals to lower trade barriers 
on services and to toughen copyright protections fearing harm to 
their infant domestic industries 
congress must approve any final agreement and the debate there 
is likely to be intense 
already special interest groups representing the american 
textile industry and peanut and sugar growers are working to build 
opposition to changes which would strip them of trade protections 
they now enjoy 
</TEXT>
