<TEXT>
columbia savings amp loan association said 
friday it lost 293 million in the first quarter as the value of 
its junk bond portfolio declined by 274 million 
but edward g harshfield columbias president and chief 
executive said the thrift had received several bids to purchase 
substantially all of its 3 billion junk bond portfolio in a 
single transaction 
the quarterly loss equal to 1462 per share contrasted with a 
profit of 79 million or 20 cents per share in the same 1989 
period 
columbia had bought more highyield highrisk junk bonds than 
any other thrift in large part due to close ties with convicted 
drexel burnham lambert inc financier michael milken whose junk 
bond network involved major thrifts 
columbia said that as of march 31 it was 338 million short of 
federal requirements for minimum capital 
the thrift said it had sold or redeemed 254 million in 
highyield bonds and preferred stock and 195 million of equity 
and equityequivalent securities 
columbia said its financial adviser first boston corp had 
received several bids to purchase nearly the entire portfolio of 
junk bonds the bids are being discussed by columbia first boston 
and the potential buyers the thrift said 
harshfield described the thrifts relationship with regulators 
as positive constructive as the thrift tries to sell of its 
junk bond portfolio 
we are also encouraged by the wide interest in the highyield 
portfolio that first boston has received so far and have a greater 
degree of confidence that a favorable transaction can occur he 
said 
columbias junk bond portfolio was worth 43 billion at the end 
of 1988 and has declined in large part because of the sharp 
decline in the highyield bond market that began last fall due to 
several prominent defaults 
the thrift has been forced to carry the junk portfolio on its 
books at market value because of accounting changes required under 
the governments bailout program for the nations saving and loan 
insurance fund 
columbia is seeking to unload the portfolio to meet net capital 
requirements for insurance the thrift is expected to receive a 
better price if it can sell the portfolio whole rather than 
piecemeal 
junk bonds are a form of debt security that offer high yields in 
exchange for their perceived high risk thrifts in the 1980s bought 
billions of dollars in the bonds which were used to finance small 
companies and hostile takeovers columbia also said it set aside 
1927 million for credit loss reserves which reflects the 
declined junk bond portfolio earlier in the quarter when it 
announced it was insolvent the thrifts accounting loss from the 
reserve for the quarter was 809 million 
due to the firstquarter loss columbia had a stockholders 
deficit of 2156 million compared with shareholders equity of 
776 million as of dec 31 
columbia said its net interest income fell to 127 million from 
602 million 
</TEXT>
