<DOCNO> AP900504-0257 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the federal communications commission ruled 
friday that the fox broadcasting co will be able to grow as a 
network while its parent company continues selling television shows 
into syndication 
the decision which grants fox a oneyear waiver to fcc 
guidelines allows the network to show up to 18 hours of 
programming a week but fox will be prohibited from acquiring any 
financial interest in or syndication rights to new programs while 
the the waiver is in effect 
before the ruling networks showing more than 15 hours of 
programming a week were forbidden by the fcc from participating in 
the television syndication business 
fox asked for the waiver in january saying the television 
market had changed substantially since the rules were adopted in 
1970 when the three major networks dominated the television market 
shows syndicated by fox inc the parent company of the network 
include a current affair mr belvedere and mash 
the ruling comes as the three networks are fighting to repeal 
the 1970 financial interest and syndication rules the rules forbid 
the networks from owning programs sold into the lucrative 
television syndication market 
the networks contend the prohibition unfairly limits their 
access to viewers 
the 3yearold fox network was awarded the limited waiver the 
fcc said because the commission wants to encourage new national 
networks help supply programming for the 112 foxaffiliated 
stations on the uhf band and advance childrens programming 
the fox network plans to introduce a 2hour daily block of 
childrens shows this fall fox also plans later this year to add 
programming on wednesday and friday night and on saturday morning 
the interim waiver announced today will permit the continued 
growth and development of fox broadcasting co as we all strive to 
achieve a global resolution of the financial interest and 
syndication issues barry diller chairman of fox inc said in a 
statement 
the ruling was opposed by the motion picture association of 
america and the walt disney co among others those opposing the 
decision fear the three established networks and fox will force 
other production companies out of business if they enter into 
syndication 
joe rutledge vice president of corporate communication for nbc 
said the network feared the ruling removes the immediate pressure 
on fox and the studios to reach a settlement on the issue of the 
financial interest and syndication rules 
he did say however that nbc applauded the fccs inclination to 
remove anticompetetive barriers from television networks 
preston padden senior vice president for affiliates for fox 
broadcasting said the network will continue to battle against the 
financial interest and syndication rules 
we are prepared to see the fight through and get appropriate 
regualatory relief for the three networks as well 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

